robeger wrote:

&gt;I was looking at your notes on 
&gt;http://www.dreamersrealm.net/tree/blog/2004/08/19/#html_only about it.  
&gt;
&gt;Sounds like what I want to do - just grab text content.  So I&#39;d guess
&gt;I need to set up mid-fetch and writer-stage ContentTypeRegExp filters
&gt;to only allow text/html and text/plain, and set up a pre-fetch
&gt;URIRegExp filter with the regexp you based on Igor&#39;s posting.
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
The above sounds like a decent tactic.

Leaving off the pre-fetch filter would mean that you&#39;d do content-type 
checks only.  Might be more suited to your purposes.  Would mean that 
the crawler does more fetches but you might get text/* content that came 
from ruled-out file endings.

&gt;Regular expressions are not my strong suit though, so would I add just
&gt;a filter for each content type, or a single combined one?
&gt;  
&gt;
One regex would probably be more performant.  Would a regex of 
&#39;^&#92;s*text/.*$&#39; suit your purposes?  This would get text/plain, 
text/html, text/xml, etc. (It matches anything that may or may not have 
leading whitespace followed by &#39;text/&#39; followed by anything).  Be aware 
that the mimetype test will go against content-type strings that could 
look like this: &#39;text/html; charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot; which you want your 
content-type regex to include (The above suggested regex will work for 
such a case).


Yours,
St.Ack

